com.camerontec.util.fixml

Class FIXMLTransformer

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.util.fixml.FIXMLTransformer
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IFromMessageTransformer, IMessageTransformer, IToMessageTransformer

    public class FIXMLTransformer
extends Object
implements IMessageTransformer
    Converts FIXML messages to and from Catalys Message objects. The main idea for the implementation of the transformer is to generate Java classes based on the FIXML XSD specification by an application which can represent FIXML elements in the transformer. Their responsibilities are to know how the represented FIXML element can be converted to a set of FIX tags and how the FIXML element itself can be built up from the related FIX tags. With this knowledge they have the ability to provide their equivalent FIX and FIXML forms. These generated classes have a common abstract superclass called FixmlElement. In this class the business logic is implemented for the transformation in methods toFIX() and toXML(). These FixmlElement classes are also aware of the information from the xsd specification which other elements can be located inside them so it means that every FIX message can be represented by a FixmlElement tree. The tree is literally the same like the elements in the FIXML version of the message. When we call toFIX() or toXML() on the root of the tree a recursive call is started which goes through on the FixmlElement tree and on the end we get the FIX or the FIXML message in String format. There are special FimlElement classes for repeating groups because obviously their behaviour is a slightly different than the normal element's. All the above works well if we have the FIX or the FIXML message represented by a FixmlElement tree but in practice we can have a FIX or FIXML message and we never get a FixmlElement tree from anywhere. It means we need to have the ability to build the FixmlElement tree from a FIX or a FIXML message. The solution is implemented inside the FixmlElement class in initFromFIX() and initFromFIXML() methods. We can build and initialize a FixmlElement tree from a FIX or a FIXML message by these methods. To initialize the tree means to fill the FixmlElement's attributes up with the actual values coming from the FIX or FIXML message. During building the tree the FixmlElements are coming from a class called FixmlRepository. Using that class we can get much better performance than to instantiate the elements because the repository works with the object cloning mechanism and it is not as expensive than creating new objects always.

    Conversion from FIX to FIXML: 1. Instantiate the root FixmlElement object: FIXML root = new FIXML(); 2. Build the FixmlElement tree up and initialize it from the FIX message: root.initFromFIX(FIX_message); 3. Get the FIXML version of the message: root.toFIXML();

    Conversion from FIXML to FIX: 1. Instantiate the root FixmlElement object: FIXML root = new FIXML(); 2. Build the FixmlElement tree up and initialize it from the FIXML message: root.initFromFIXML(FIXML_message); 3. Get the FIX version of the message: root.toFIX(); The application to generate the FixmlElements is called FixmlElementGenerator. This standalone Java application generates the source code for every FixmlElement class except the root FIXML class. The generated source code should be compiled and the elements should be placed into a separated jar file. The root FixmlElement (FIXML.class) is placed into the main Catalys core jar. The advantage of the separation of the generated code is the customization. Customers can create their own FIXML XSD specification and generate the related FixmlElements and use them. If they have custom elements or attributes in their FIXML messages but they have not modified the XSD and using the default implementation which is based on the standard FIXML 4.4 specification they can use the ignoreUndefiniedAttributes and ignoreUndefinedElements attributes for the FixmlTransformer and it will ignore the custom elements and attributes. In default the transformer gives an error message when something appears in the messages which is not a valid component according to the specification.

    Author:
    Imre Aranyosi
